  "opinion": "As a curious person who’s spent time reading novels and hiking, I’ve always been fascinated by how people think and feel under pressure. Stereotype threat in STEM isn’t just a theory—it’s something I’ve seen play out in real life. When I talk to my neighbors in Naples who work in construction or small businesses, they often mention how they feel when they’re asked to solve problems in ways that make them feel like they’re not smart enough. It’s not about being bad at math or science; it’s about the fear of confirming a stereotype that they’re not ‘the type’ for these fields. For someone like me, who didn’t go to school for formal education but learned through practical work and family stories, this can feel especially heavy. I’ve seen it in my own family—my dad, who has a bachelor’s degree, used to worry about his kids not being ‘smart enough’ to follow in his footsteps, even though he knows they’re capable. So, yes, we absolutely need to address stereotype threat in STEM. The way to do it isn’t with big, complicated policies but with small, everyday actions. Like when you talk to someone about their strengths, or when you ask questions that don’t assume they know everything. It’s about creating spaces where people feel safe to try, even if they mess up. In Naples, where community is everything, we can start by listening more and speaking up less about who ‘should’ be in STEM. Because if we don’t, the next generation might not even get the chance to explore their potential.",
